@node "Features" "Feature List"
 @{i}@{u}@{fg shine}Feature List@{ui}@{uu}@{fg text}

MEAGORComm is jam-packed with features, some of which have never been seen
before on ANY Amiga package.

It is the most easy to use Terminal software you'll find!


Here's some of the features
 '@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text}' indicates not in demo - @{b}@{bg fill}@{"BUY THE FULL VERSION" link "Registering" 0}

@{bg back}----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Runs under KS1.2+

New easy to use Gui system without large memory restraints.

Help text at the bottom of every window, just move the mouse over the button,
text box, or what ever is troubling you.

@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} Programmable Buttonbar which uses its on screen and pallette.

Modular preferences for every BBS.

Graphics Terminal supporting many new commands such as IFF Graphics, Sound ST
modules, Mouse zones/buttons, Copper effects,  Colour effects and many more.
THIS IS THE BEST FEATURE OF ALL!

Allows user to automatically send their Username and Password when the BBS
requests it with a command (NO script programing required)

@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} A Files/Ratio database - records which files you up/download to each BBS.
and * calculated your ratio or warns you if you try to upload them again to
the same * BBS.

ANSI Music - Up to now only PC terminals supported this.

@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} Upload list editor - choose the files you want to upload before logging on.
@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} to save time and money

Stretchy Chat window - @{i}Oh yes@{ui}:)


The @{i}Not-so@{ui} Unique features

@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} ARexx port for automation of repetitive tasks etc.

Comprehensive Phonebook and Preferences manager.

@{b}@{fg shine}*@{ub}@{fg text} Macro keys

ASCII Text Capture to File or Printer

Save the screen as an IFF picture.

ANSI Graphics - @{i}obviously@{ui}:)
@endnode

@node "Intro" "Introduction"
@{i}Grovelling...@{ui}

Meet the poorest programmer in the world (probably), I'm 17 year old student
and jobless, we don't have jobs or local BBS in Cornwall, just Pasties and I
really need some money before I can continue to develop this software further
since testing is expensive @{"(Big sorry to all the BBS I've crashed)" link "Thanks" 0} So If you
can afford it then please consider @{"buying the full version." link "Registering" 0}


@{i}Programmed Using@{ui}

This program was originally designed and programmed using an unexpanded
Amiga1200. I now have a 2 meg expansion card since it wouldn't compile without
one:( Hopefully this means that it will work on almost any Amiga.


@{i}Why the stupid name?@{ui}

There are thousands of programmers around, I know the names of about 5 so I
thought if I named it after myself then people might remember it (???)
(Programming Job offers welcome:-) )


@{i}Why did I write this program?@{ui}

Well it started off with me trying to get an NComm script to change the screen
font according to commands sent from the BBS but it refused to work so I
installed Term, but no luck there either.  Term is far too memory hungry
anyway. On a standard 2meg machine you don't get much left to spare:(

I then got the idea of creating a custom terminal which could be connected to
NComm with an @{"ARexx" link "ARexx Port" 0} script.  That Idea grew and eventually I decided to go all
out and beat the other terminals at their own game - I think I've succeded
too:-) [Just in  case there's anyone left on the planet whos never come
accross a smiley before @{"Click Here" link "Smileys" 0}]


The program was origionally designed to work on ANY AMIGA with a Hard Drive
and shuld run on a 1Meg computer but if you intend to use ot for the @{"NEW set" link "Graphics Description" 0}
@{"of commands" link "Graphics Description" 0} then 2 or more megs would be better depending on how the BBS
@{"SysOps" link "SysOps" 0} decide to use it.


...'nuff of all that, @{"install" link "Installing" 0} it now, go on, you know you want to:-)


Note: Their are loads of spelling mistakes in this manual, and well, I don't
really care:-)
@endnode

@node "Requirments" "Requirments"
@{i}Minimum Requirments@{ui}

 Kickstart 1.2+
 1meg of memory


@{i}Recommended@{ui}

 2megs+
 A Hard Drive


For plain ANSI BBS you could probably get a way with the minimum requirments
but you will probably have problems downloading files to to a disk drive
through space and speed limitations.

People with slow modems - you might find the new codes faster than the old
ANSI codes since less information is being transmitted across the line.
@endnode

@node "Installing" "Installing MEAGORComm"
    MEAGORComm comes complete with a standard Amiga installer script which
should always be used to install the program rather than by hand.


@{i}What the script does@{ui}

 1) Creates a directory on your HD.
 2) Copies across the software.
 3) Copies across the system librarys.
 3) Creates some blank directories (ie. Downloads, Uploads, Captures etc).
 4) Places the line
                    @{fg shine}Assign MEAGORComm: <Wherever it's been installed>@{fg text}

 All operations are verified first.
@endnode

@node "Graphics Description" "NEW Graphics Terminal"
@{u}@{fg shine}The Multimedia Engine!@{uu}@{fg text}

I could see no reason why we should stick to crap text based displays when we
have the capabillity of using pictures, sound and animation, after all the
Amiga is the ideal platform for Multimedia so this is what I've come up with.

@{i}Support for@{ui}

 IFF Pictures.
 Bitmap fonts
 IFF and RAW Sounds.
 Sound/Noise Tracker music support
 Text/graphics buttons (mouse operated).
 Various mouse commands.
 Basic drawing commands - line, box, circle, pixel etc.
 Copper/rainbow effects.
 Pallette changes, fades, cycling.
 REALTIME EXECUTION - no waiting for an entire script to be downloaded.

I don't think I've left anything of importance out although if you have any
suggestions then please @{"send them to me" link "Registering" 0} and perhaps I'll include them in the
next version.
@endnode

@node "Smileys" "Smileys"
@{u}@{fg shine}Comms Jargon@{uu}@{fg text}

Comms is notorious for it's use of abbreviations and jargon.  To save any new
users embarissment heres what a few of them mean.


@{i}Smileys@{ui}

A smiley is just a couple of characters used to express an emotion.

:-)    This is the most common smiley, if you don't see it then turn your head
sideways, see it grinning at you!

@{i}Heres a brief list of smilies@{ui}

:-(         Sad smiley....ahhhh

:-/         Confused smiley.

#-/         Stoned smiley.

*-=:-)      Santa smiley.

:)          Smiley smiley.

:(          Not so smiley smiley.


@{i}Ok enougth with the damm smileys, heres a couple of abbreviations.@{ui}

ROTFL       Rolling on the floor laughing.

IMHO        In my honest opinion.

IMO         In my opinion.

BTW         By the way.


@{i}Finally@{ui}

Writing in capatals is considered to be shouting so don't use continually.
Puting '*' around some text means shouting *REALLY* loud.

I think that should do to start with.
@endnode

@node "SysOps" "SysOps"
@{u}@{fg shine}A SysOp@{uu}@{fg text}

A SysOp is the person who runs the BBS, Usually at great financial loss so be
considerate towards them.
@endnode

